eption;\nimport java.io.FileOutputStream;\nimport java.io.FilenameFilter;\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.InputStream;\nimport java.io.OutputStream;\nimport java.net.URL;\nimport java.util.Random;\n\nimport org.hsqldb.lib.java.JavaSystem;\n\n/**\n * A collection of file management methods.<p>\n * Also provides the default FileAccess implementation\n *\n * @author Campbell Burnet (campbell-burnet@users dot sourceforge.net)\n * @author Fred Toussi (fredt@users dot sourceforge.net)\n * @author Ocke Janssen oj@openoffice.org\n * @version 2.4.1\n * @since 1.7.2\n */\npublic class FileUtil implements FileAccess {\n\n    private static final FrameworkLogger LOG =\n        FrameworkLogger.getLog(FileUtil.class);\n    private static FileUtil      fileUtil      = new FileUtil();\n    private static FileAccessRes fileAccessRes = new FileAccessRes();\n\n    /** Creates a new instance of FileUtil */\n    FileUtil() {}\n\n    public static FileUtil getFileUtil() {\n        return fileUtil;\n    }\n\n[587 more lines in file. Use offset=71 to continue.]"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1777931704731}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering resource handling in tests**\n\nI think I need to use AssertJ for my testing framework, and I wonder if tests need to compile independently? I'm contemplating about how the `FileAccessRes` constructor works, particularly if its methods should be marked with @Override. Also, I’m considering wrapping certain methods with throwables. The focus might be testing the resource methods, ensuring coverage reports are accurate in terms of efficient calls. It could be good to establish test scenarios that manage both class-relative resources and context classloader fallbacks effectively.\n\n**Evaluating resource loading strategy**\n\nI’m thinking about whether I need to add test resource metadata if I use a custom URL. The `getResource` method from the class loader might be my custom override, returning a URL pointing to a temporary file, which wouldn't require resource metadata. I should consider testing how `getResourceAsStream` works with ByteArrayInputStream. \n\nI might focus on a specific test scenario for fallback behavior by setting the context loader, ensuring the test covers various outcomes with relative names. I'll use unique names to avoid conflicts, just in case resources unexpectedly exist.\n\n**Exploring custom classloader functionality**\n\nI'm considering that my custom classloader can return exact resource URLs, which means I might not need any test resources since everything can be managed in memory. I'm thinking about how `getResource` could return a URL, and I'm curious if I can create a URL using a custom stream handler. This might allow me to return the URL data seamlessly. It’s an interesting direction to consider for resource management and testing!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_03c5a92e4e9128da0169f915ab7040819d8b881f6ca37e25f6\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-RW4FeL-mFPUAkyepZAf2tFh7E0XlPLSs5ZDPohSS